<dns_rebinding_attacks>
<concept>
{% raw %}
# DNS rebinding bypasses localhost/internal IP restrictions
# 1. Initial DNS resolution returns attacker IP (passes whitelist check)
# 2. Subsequent resolution returns internal IP (127.0.0.1, 169.254.169.254)
# 3. If application caches DNS briefly, second request hits internal service

# Tools: rebinder.app, 1u.ms, nip.io (for specific IPs)
{% endraw %}
</concept>

<techniques>
{% raw %}
# Multiple A records technique
# DNS returns both attacker IP and internal IP
# Random selection may hit internal target

# Time-based rebinding
# Use very low TTL (0-1 seconds)
# Change DNS response after first request

# Services:
http://7f000001.1u.ms/ → resolves to 127.0.0.1
http://a9fea9fe.1u.ms/ → resolves to 169.254.169.254

# Custom rebinding domains
# Setup DNS server that changes responses based on query count
# First query: return 1.2.3.4 (attacker controlled)
# Second query: return 127.0.0.1 or 169.254.169.254
{% endraw %}
</techniques>

<bypass_toctou>
{% raw %}
# Time-of-check to time-of-use (TOCTOU) race
# 1. Application checks if domain is allowed (DNS resolves to safe IP)
# 2. Application makes request (DNS now resolves to internal IP)
# Window: Between DNS check and actual request

# Maximize success:
# - Use very low TTL
# - Make multiple parallel requests
# - Application may cache DNS for different duration than expected
{% endraw %}
</bypass_toctou>
</dns_rebinding_attacks>

