<validation>
1. Prove server-initiated request to internal/cloud resource (OOB callback or metadata access)
2. Demonstrate credential/token extraction from cloud metadata
3. Show impact escalation (RCE, lateral movement, data access)
4. Provide reproducible payloads with exact bypass techniques used
5. Document which protections were bypassed (URL filters, DNS checks, etc.)
</validation>

<false_positives>
- Client-side only requests (JavaScript fetch, no server involvement)
- Strict allowlists with DNS pinning and redirect blocking
- Proper IMDSv2 enforcement with method restrictions
- Network segmentation preventing metadata access
- All protocols except HTTP/HTTPS blocked at application level
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Cloud credentials exposure (AWS keys, GCP tokens, Azure MSI)
- Access to internal services and admin panels
- Remote code execution via protocol exploitation
- Kubernetes/Docker API access enabling container escape
- Lateral movement within cloud infrastructure
- Data exfiltration from internal databases and services
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Always start with OOB (DNS/HTTP) to confirm blind SSRF
2. Test all protocol handlers available in the technology stack
3. Cloud detection: try metadata endpoints immediately
4. IMDSv2 bypass: look for PUT method support or header injection
5. DNS rebinding works best with parallel requests
6. Gopher protocol is extremely powerful for Redis/Memcached
7. Combine SSRF with other vulns (XXE, SSTI, file upload)
8. Check for SSRF in less obvious places (webhooks, import/export, analytics)
9. Use timing differences for blind port scanning
10. Document cloud credentials but don't use them without permission
11. Chain quickly: metadata → credentials → API access (minimal impact demo)
12. Test both IPv4 and IPv6 addresses
13. URL parsers differ: what browser allows vs backend library
14. Redirects are powerful bypass mechanisms
15. Background jobs often have fewer SSRF protections
</pro_tips>

<remember>Advanced SSRF is about understanding the full attack surface: cloud providers, protocol handlers, bypass techniques, and chaining to achieve maximum impact. Every cloud deployment is vulnerable to metadata SSRF unless IMDSv2 is properly enforced. Blind SSRF with OOB callbacks is the standard validation method. Focus on demonstrating impact while minimizing actual damage.</remember>
</ssrf_advanced_vulnerability_guide>
